Food Debt in European Inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, inflation was higher in November than expected - after the 2.6% in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are based on only 3%, reports Bloomberg.
In contrast to the US, UK, and Canadian notes bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzsins. Its discretion is that the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment in the creation of an inflation spiral.
The ECB is committed to keeping the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two-percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the middle of the coin: inflation must be "agreed" to exclude the need for action later on.
With 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in November in Germany; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in inflation in the euro area is responsible for rising food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts assume a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
In 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
