Disinfectants are saved in many places
More than a thousand infections were recorded in hospitals, due to improper treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overstocking of the beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that do not exactly contribute to the control of the infections, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital, MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was a similar infection here.
The injury of a major car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December of this year, infections to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System were reported from hospitals in 1094 by multi-resistant pathogens, according to the senior physician of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the dark number is probably higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by the MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as cervical inflammation, almond inflammation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are dosed too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotics-resistant, which spread rapidly in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with impaired, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the daily hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to Antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA when they are sent to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample withdrawals too rarely
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable for limiting the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients who have been delivered and immediately isolate MRSA infected patients.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not so often practiced.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation from the public health insurance fund.
Therefore, most cases would not come to light until the patient has already had a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and disease patterns in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological investigations are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but this directive of hospitals is not always complied with.
Among the outpatient or basic patients, microbiological sampling is even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
It is saved in disinfectants.
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted by nurses from one patient to another.
That is why handwashing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröcz further notes, in the financially less well-off hospitals, it even occurs that in disinfectants is saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that directly favour the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infections in the control of the health insurance causes enormous costs, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its mitigation has been retained in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals to be one of its priorities.
