Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries advise on Bali's roadmap setting out the emission-reducing measures for the post-2012 period, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between industrialized and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to support both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on the support of developing countries has also been reached.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, likely to be managed by the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as reflected in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6 percent
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of the Environment Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by the 1990 figures), regardless of whether the "after 2012" agreement was achieved successfully, or not. The Union would even be willing to support a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialized countries in the world, or developing countries, are also prepared to meet their commitments by strength and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the States that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU and its 15 Member States had already committed to a reduction of 8%.
The objective for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that will be fully met, as can be seen in the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project defined in the Kyoto-defined reduction project would not follow a renewed international emission reduction system, whose importance was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international Nobel Peace Prize Scientific Climate Change Committee of the UN in its recent report.
This would delay emission reduction, and increasing Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which according to scientists would lead to extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
