Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of re-disposing the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year gives us less such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and non-working days.
Working days are mostly church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: Both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone can rest with the New Year's celebrations.
All year round we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are March 15th, which commemorates the 1848 Revolution, and October 23rd, the anniversary of the 1956 Revolution.
On August 20th, the founding of the state, celebrated on May 1st, on November 1st and 2nd, we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our public, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be completed, the Minister of Labour has been in a separate regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, to public employees and civil servants of the public service.
Only companies and establishments in which the operation is continued without interruption, including during the holidays, are excluded.
Today, the working order is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country remains formal, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve take time compensation, or the holiday that has been specifically withdrawn.
Next year more holidays will fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so that there will be fewer re-dispositions during the working days than this year.
The calendar is first put "on the head" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at the same time.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 may be a day of rest.
The second re-disposition is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to finish Friday, October 24th in advance.
The end of the year, however, will remain in the sign of the holidays, after everything will be left from 24 December, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
