A heavy reminder
After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located in Bad Arolsen on a total length of 27 km, have so far not been understood, except with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and by name, that is, on the request of a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, the eleven States entrusted with their administration – including Germany, France, Israel and the USA – agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Secret Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable researchers to carry out investigations, especially about the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health status of forced workers, explains Reto Meisteren, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoners' lists of the concentration camps or the warrants issued by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen handle tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
There must be nothing fundamentally new in these documents, explained by Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
