New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is floating between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports being affected by fuel to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are directed by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit charges from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent conflict between Kiev and Moscow occurs at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be more calculated as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% in addition for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in discussions," said the Minister of Economic Affairs of Ukraine Anatoli Kinakh of the news agency Reuters.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This resulted in a case of exports to Western Europe, which dramatically boosted prices.
Russian gas represents a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
