The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of the pre-punishment registers for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish state health service has no precise idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly on a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area following the attack at Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a field car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission in October and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in Great Britain.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to the appointment of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review pre-punitive records, the Agency does not have the power to obtain such information outside the UK.
The main auditor's report now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the Executive Board should take up guidelines from the Penal Register Extract, which helps employers to check in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel documents, they have not been routinely carried out." the report noted.
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigation guidelines to a high degree before recruitment, but added: "Our report shows areas in which the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health care workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in the run-up to the appointment of potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that the NHS Scotland's current pre-selection tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the board had problems identifying those employees who had left for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation continued that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were largely complied with.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
The Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said, "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines regarding control investigations would be reflected in the run-up to the appointment of all employees - including those from abroad - whose publication is planned next month.
