They're not Warhol's boxes.
Those who combine the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, in Sweden, wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of the "Type Stockholm" are forgerys.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" some months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now coming to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave the Moderna Museet 1995 as a gift, are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately one hundred further broillo boxes of the "Type Stockholm" that are in circulation on the international art market.
The history is nested, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes", painted wooden boxes, based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard cartons of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of broillo boxes made of cardboard: these were (for cost reasons) not from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not works of art, it was examples of them, merely pieces of exhibition.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at the time have rightly entered art and auction history as authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than 100,000 dollars at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later mistakenly claimed that it was produced and exhibited around a hundred wooden boxes in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined the six museum's own Brillo boxes, three of which were produced in Stockholm in 1968: their press boards were first founded and sanded, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressboard with a painting roll without primer - in addition, it is not oil but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would follow the "severe accusations" that are being made in the matter of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, there has been an inexorable silence.
